The paper deals with the analysis of communication performance of random linear vector channels, which is a topic in information theory (cs.IT). The paper also presents a computationally feasible algorithm for decoding received signals, which falls under the category of numerical analysis (cs.NA). The use of statistical mechanics and probability theory in the analysis suggests that the paper may also be relevant to the sub-categories of statistical inference (cs.SI) and machine learning (cs.MM). Finally, the paper's focus on analyzing large random matrices suggests that it may also be relevant to the sub-category of large-scale data analysis (cs.LG).
